  "signature": "ed25519:b4e8d2f6a0c4e8b2d6f0a4c8e2b6d0f4a8c2e6b0d4f8a2c6e0b4d8f2a6c0e4b8",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/sqa-001",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/sqa-mrl2",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2) is a commercially validated platform with documented V&V procedures. Version control is maintained via institutional license management and all simulation scripts are stored in a tracked repository. SQA level 2 is satisfied by documented solver release notes, regression test suite results, and internal SOP for simulation workflow management."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/ncv-002",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/ncv-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Numerical code verification was performed through the method of manufactured solutions for the incompressible Navier-Stokes solver and confirmed second-order spatial convergence. The hemolysis power-law model implementation was independently verified against published analytical test cases from Giersiepen et al. and Heuser & Opitz. All verification cases are archived in the simulation quality record."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/de-003",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/de-mrl2",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study was conducted using Richardson extrapolation following the Celik et al. (2008) ASME procedure. The grid convergence index (GCI) for the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) was 1.4% on the fine mesh (18.7M cells), 3.1% on the medium mesh (7.2M cells), and 8.9% on the coarse mesh (2.1M cells). The fine mesh was selected for all production runs, yielding an achieved level of 3, exceeding the MRL 2 requirement of level 2."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/tc-004",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/tc-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions from the FDA benchmark hemolysis study (Hariharan et al. 2011) were replicated in the CFD boundary conditions. Inlet flow rates of 2, 3, 4, 5, and 6 L/min at rotational speeds of 2000, 2500, and 3500 RPM were matched. Blood viscosity was modeled as Newtonian (mu = 0.0035 Pa·s) consistent with the experimental protocol. Temperature was fixed at 37°C for all cases."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/oc-005",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/oc-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values were compared against published experimental measurements from the FDA benchmark study across all 15 operating points. The mean absolute percentage error was 12.3%, within the accepted tolerance band for hemolysis CFD predictions at MRL 2. Bland-Altman analysis confirmed no systematic bias across the flow-speed operating envelope."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/rqoi-006",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/rqoi-mrl2",
      "rationale": "The primary quantity of interest is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) computed via the Eulerian scalar transport approach with the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law damage accumulation model. NIH is the clinically and regulatorily recognized metric for pump-induced hemolysis and directly maps to the device submission acceptance criterion of RH < 1 relative to the predicate. Secondary QoIs include wall shear stress distribution and scalar stress exposure histograms."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/rvac-007",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "The validation activities are directly relevant to the COU because the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry used in the benchmark experiments is geometrically and operationally analogous to the subject CPB device. Operating conditions span the clinical flow-speed envelope for CPB (2–6 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM). The hemolysis model form, boundary conditions, and post-processing methodology used in validation are identical to those applied in the COU predictions. The validation dataset encompasses the full range of operating points assessed in the COU, including the five worst-case candidates identified by the sensitivity analysis. Prior publications by Morrison et al. (2016) and Malinauskas et al. (2017) have independently confirmed the suitability of the FDA benchmark as a surrogate for Class II CPB device hemolysis assessment. The validation team included three independent CFD analysts who reviewed boundary condition setup, mesh topology, and post-processing scripts before any production runs were executed, providing an additional layer of assurance that the validation activities faithfully represent the intended COU. Internal peer review documentation (Ref. QPR-2024-CFD-07) is archived in the device technical file and available for regulatory inspection. On this basis, the relevance of validation activities is assessed as meeting level 2 without reservation."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/nse-008",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/nse-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error is scoped to level 1 at MRL 2 for this COU. Iterative convergence was monitored via residual norms (all below 1e-5) and mass flux imbalance (below 0.01%). No further assessment is required at this model risk level."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/ue-009",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/ue-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Use error assessment is not required beyond level 1 at MRL 2. Simulation execution followed a documented SOP with mandatory independent review of case setup files prior to submission. No use errors were identified during the review."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/mf-010",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/mf-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty is acknowledged but not formally assessed at MRL 2. The k-omega SST turbulence model was selected based on literature consensus for rotating machinery hemolysis prediction. A sensitivity comparison with realizable k-epsilon was performed informally and showed less than 8% difference in NIH, supporting the model form selection."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/mi-011",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/mi-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Model input uncertainty is not formally assessed at MRL 2. Nominal material properties (blood density 1056 kg/m3, dynamic viscosity 0.0035 Pa·s) are well-established in the literature and consistent with the experimental benchmark protocol. Geometric inputs are derived from the FDA-published CAD files."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/ts-012",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/ts-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Test sample characterization beyond level 1 is not required at MRL 2. The experimental hemolysis data used for validation was obtained using bovine blood with documented hematocrit and plasma free hemoglobin baseline measurements consistent with ASTM F1841 guidance."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/eip-013",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/eip-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters between the validation case and the COU is acknowledged at a qualitative level consistent with MRL 2 requirements. The FDA benchmark pump geometry and the subject CPB device share the same impeller topology and operating envelope, supporting the assumption of parameter equivalency for the purposes of this assessment."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/decision/dr-cou1-cpb-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
